WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:20.000
This is Emily Crosby on December 9, 2015 with Judy Richardson and we're in her home in Silver Spring, Maryland, outside of DC.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And we're here with the Civil Rights History Project, co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:35.000
And also with us are John Bishop and Lou Haas-Shanker. Judy, thank you so much for doing our interview.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Thank you. Can you start by telling us when and where you were born and about your family?

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:48.000
I was born on March 10, 1944 in Tarrytown, New York, which is about 45 miles north of New York City.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:58.000
My mother, Melee Louise Richardson, newly Tucker, was first a seamstress and then a homemaker.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Married to my father and my father was a... Oh, and also she was a jazz pianist, but I can get to that in a minute.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Yeah, oh, honey, played a mean jazz piano. But my father was William King Richardson and he grew up in the house that I grew up in and that he married and took my mother to in Tarrytown and the under the hill section.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:24.000
It's called that of Tarrytown, which is where all the blue collar folks lived right near the railroad tracks.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:40.000
My father had helped to organize the United Auto Workers' Local in what was called the plant, which was the Fisher Body Chevrolet Plant, where my father and the fathers of everybody I knew worked.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And you could tell time from the shifts changing at the plant.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And I found out only after my older sister saw a one of the many documentary series that Blackside had done after I was on the prize and it was on the depression.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And the beginning segment of that was on the beginnings of the Ford Factory. That was the first segment.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And she saw all of the archival material from that and what it looked like in the plant. And she called me and she said, oh, I just saw Blacksides and it reminded me of when Daddy was organizing the local.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:32.000
And this is news to me. So I said, what? And she said, yeah, Daddy was working in the plant and she said there were times when he had decided he wanted to organize a union and the UAW local there.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:40.000
And so she said what I remember, what she, my sister remembered, was that when the guy from the nationally was a white guy.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And so he would come up and sit in my kitchen talking to my father. And what my sister said was that my mother would immediately close the curtains because we were ground level.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:04.000
We had a little teeny tiny little house right on the ground there. And she said she would immediately close the curtains so that nobody could see that my father was talking to somebody from the local, from the national.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Because she was afraid of course with good reason that he might lose his job.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Did you have a sense of the time? I have this.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Not really. I mean, I have no memory of it. And so it would have had to be when he, so he dies on the assembly line when I'm seven years old. He dies of a heart attack.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And so that would have been probably 53, 4 and 7 is 11, 51, 51. So I was seven years old and he, oh, when the other thing she remembers about this is that sometimes people would leave groceries, bags of groceries on our porch.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:55.000
Because they would be too afraid to overtly say they were supporting the local and the building of the organizing of the local.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
But the way they did that was to then give my family some groceries.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:08.000
And so I'll keep my sister, Carita said, you know, you would come down outside and you would find these bags of groceries on the porch.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And the result was that as one of the white guys in Tarry Town mentioned to me when we were protesting segregated housing, why are you doing this? He said, we loved Billy, my father, which they did. They loved Billy.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Now they wouldn't allow him and some other stuff, but they loved Billy because he had, you know, he was treasure of that local when he died of a heart attack on the line, you know, in 51.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:43.000
So yeah, there's all of that. So your dad's helping to organize a union that's mostly white and he wants to be?

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:58.000
No, there weren't no, no, because Tarry Town had a, I would say about a 10% black population. And like all of the white ethnic on our block, because my block, there was the projects down the road. And that was just about all black.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And then on our block, which again was under the hill, so we nobody had any money, but they were all working class, my family, and then the working class, white people on the block, Italians, Polish, and Irish.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:26.000
And so in addition though, and I should mention by the way that Tarry Town was steeped in tradition. So I went to Washington Irving, junior high school. This was Washington Irving's territory.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:39.000
Washington Irving's, Washington Irving, junior high school, sleepy hollow high school. Yes, our mascot was the headless horseman, a horseman goat. It was all of that. I mean, we had, you know,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:50.000
and, but I didn't see any middle class, certainly no middle class black people, but no middle class white people either, because it hadn't become that kind of suburban thing.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:06:08.000
There were white people who lived in sleepy hollow manner and tap and see something like that. But most of the people I knew, and certainly all my friends, were white kids, some black kids, but mainly white kids whose parents, whose father worked in the plant,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:20.000
the black people I knew their mothers mainly, their fathers worked in the plant too, and their mothers oftentimes worked out so they were domestic workers.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Yeah.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:31.000
Well, I was just so when, when people are saying you really love Billy, why are you doing this kind of thing, that's because you're protesting segregation.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Segregated housing, housing, but also on my block at the end of my block was a fire department, and it was all volunteers. You know, I mean, it's Tarry Town.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And so they had no, I mean, none of the fire departments had any black people. So when I come back from SNCC, that first summer, which would have been 60, I guess the summer is 64 somewhere in there, not only have we already started a Tarry Town or civil rights, but also with this wonderful black couple, Ogalli, who was a doctor, oh, I may or may not remember her name.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:18.000
She and her husband both, both black, she was the doctor, and he was an architect, and they moved on Broadway, and that was major.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:38.000
I mean, when I went back to speak at Marymount College in Tarry Town, they came as did a number of former folks from Tarry Town as civil rights, and I went up to her husband, and I said, oh my gosh, you know you were the first black couple to actually make it to Broadway, you know, and he said, you know, all the black people told us that, you know, so it was great.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Yeah, but so we're doing stuff around residential, but it's also specific to that fire department. Now, when we pull up a picket line, it's on the end of my block, right, 133 Franklin Street was my town, right, was my address.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:02.000
At the end of that block, we had a picket line, and it was at a corner where all the commuters, because there were commuters.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:10.000
I just didn't know any of them because they were white in middle class, but they would come through that when they got off the train, because we're right across from the train, right.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:21.000
So they would see the picket line, and we had thrown it up because, you know, they blackpoles, and they said that, we blackpoles, you know, and I remember one guy coming, oh what?

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
What does that mean for young people to know?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Yes, good point. Blackpoles, and during the certain times when we were trying to rearrange the language, we started calling it whitepoles.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:50.000
But blackpoles meant that you did not, one blackpoles, it was kind of like you would put, well, I guess in terms of the fire department, it meant that if there was any neighborhood on a proposed person who would be invited in to be part of the city,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
it would be part of the volunteer fire department.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Then somebody would either put a black ball, or put a black piece of paper, something to indicate, nay.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:08.000
But the ball, oftentimes I guess how it started, was that it would be a ball, it would be a little black ball that would mean that was a no vote.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Did that automatically look any blackpoles?

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:19.000
Yes, and what they reminded me of, and this was while I'm on the picket line, they reminded me that, first of all, yes, we loved Billy.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:35.000
But also, that when our house caught fire, Thanksgiving day, and we had gone out of town to my father's family, and in Yonkers, nearby, came back and found smoldering.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:47.000
I mean, they hit, it was just, and one of them, my mother reminded me of this. She said that one of the firemen who loved Billy, said, you know,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:54.000
I stopped one of the other firemen from using a hatchet on the door, because I said, no, this is Billy's house.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And I'm sure he did that, because that was separate.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:06.000
So, yeah, with smoldering, you know, remember we all, you know, were in there, it was cold, because we couldn't put any heat on.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:13.000
But eventually, I got back to whatever, and it didn't burn down, it just was very smoldering, and we couldn't have any heat.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And it was thanksgiving and cold and stuff, yeah. So anyway, there were fond memories of my father.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And we also picketed, again, after I come back from that first stint in SNIC.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:38.000
So I'm taking a break, we're fundraising for SNIC. And it must have been, I can't remember if it was before or after the 64 Summer Project and Mississippi.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:47.000
But certainly, we're doing some kind of fundraising. And so I bring Stokely, the Freedom Singer, so Bernice and Chuck and Rutha.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:56.000
And I don't know who the other, who was the other, in that original group, it wasn't Matthew, who's the other guy?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Oh, and Cordell, yeah, Cordell, hello. So they come up, and they, so Stokely speaks.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:14.000
Now this is before Black Power, so it's 64. Stokely speaks, the Freedom, SNIC Freedom Singer's sing, and it's in Patriots Park in front of the library.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:29.000
There was a woman, Mrs. Kenny, who was as right wing as you could get her. And so she protested about how in Patriots Park, there were these Communists singing these songs, and we all know they were Communists.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:40.000
She had written the letter saying that SNIC was a Communist, well, basically what did they used to call them, not supporters.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:50.000
Sympathizer, yeah. And so she put this in the Tarry Town Daily News. Now my mother wrote, I mean, she had a beautiful handwriting. I mean, it was gorgeous.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:59.000
My mother had like an eighth grade education, right. She read everything. Every Sunday it was meet the press on the television.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:11.000
I remember her, she had stacks of the New York Post, which then was a real newspaper, right. And she would love Mary Kempton's articles because he was a little leftist, he was a liberal, basically.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And so she had all these stacks on her in her bedroom. And she would write back to Mrs. Kenny in the Tarry Town Daily News and say, no, you know, did it, did it, and very rational.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:36.000
Mrs. Kenny at one point said something about which I had to respond to, but had said something about we know that they are coming to Sympathizers because it was read into the Congressional record.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And it's like you could be the phone book into the Congressional record, but she didn't know any better.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:48.000
So there was always that kind of, you know, it's kind of like the Tea Party now, you know, that's it.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So, but my mother would, you know, respond. And then I have letters from her, you know, where she's saying that I shouldn't, I should be careful and not, you know, be around people because I'm going to be, I'm going to get a cold.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:14.000
And she said, stay away from anybody who's sneezing because I've just realized that's part of what got lost at that Duke interview.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:26.000
But I have the original letter from her where she talks about, you know, staying away from anybody who's cold, you know, who has a cold in the sneezing.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:37.000
And then she says, now, of course, this is, I'm in Mississippi and it's 1964. And she's talking about worry about the people who were sneezing because they may give you a cold.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And then, really thinking about that. Well, then her next line is something about, you know, I got to get to bed now. I haven't been sleeping well.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And it was only after I got grown and looked at this letter, not back then, that I realized she's not sleeping because she's worried sick about me, right?

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:05.000
But she's not saying any of that in the letter. And she says in the letter something about, you know, and key to my sister, Carita, is cooking, can Duke Thanksgiving dinner because she's organizing parties.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Now, the parties were that I had brought my sister in and my sister was now organizing the Harry Belafonte parties in 1964 on Long Island out of the SNCC fundraising office in New York City.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:30.000
And so my sister who could really cook, unlike my mother, excuse me, my sister could cook. And so she was going to usually could do the turkey, but no, she's doing the Belafonte concerts.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Yeah.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
So, how do I go back?

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
Yes.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Sorry, no, I go off.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:40.000
Yes.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:46.000
You know, but so you found out later from your sister that your father was organizing.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Yes.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
And you died on the line in your seven.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And what was your mother doing?

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:53.000
Yes, good point.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:00.000
So, my mother, at some point my mother, well, my mother could play piano.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
I mean, she could hear something and could just do chords.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And so she had written music. She read certainly read scores and stuff, but she'd music.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And she loved working in best. She had all that sheet music in the bench.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:20.000
But in addition, she could play all kinds of things. And she loved, you know, Oscar Peterson.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
And she just loved lots of people. So, mm-hmm.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:27.000
Not Oscar, be artedim. She loved artedim.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:31.000
So, for her own amusement, she is doing this.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
But before I'm born, I think, before I'm born.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:40.000
She was the pianist in a little jazz combo in Westchester County, which is where Terry Tendless.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And so she was going around playing as the pianist with this Teddy Whiteley Orchestra.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
Until my father stopped it.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And I guess he didn't want his wife going off when he was not there on site, you know,

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
and off to these little clubs and stuff.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.000
Oh, jazz.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:58.000
You got it.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
A little free, yes. Although my mother was so prim. But anyway, so.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:08.000
So, in any event, so she's not doing that, but she's still always played.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:13.000
I mean, I always remember my mother playing to the point that when I come back from,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
and I got to tell you about the numbers because she also booked the numbers.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:23.000
But when I come back from 64 from Mississippi,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:28.000
she's sitting in our little living room on the bench and in front of the piano.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And it was a little small piano.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And she said, come here, come here.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
And I go over and I sit next to her on the bench.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.000
And she started playing. We shall overcome with these blue chords.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
I still remember it. It's like it just brought tears to me.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
You know, it was like, oh, my little mommy.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
You know, it was so cute. It was so cute.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.000
And they were so gorgeous. I mean, I had never heard.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:59.000
We shall overcome that way. You know, it's just, it was just gorgeous.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
Yeah. And she, I mean, she had heard it.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
It wasn't like she was reading, you know, sheet music.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
She just heard the chords, you know.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:12.000
And so also though, what my mother did was that she booked numbers.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
So since she wasn't playing in the orchestra anymore.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And she booked numbers for including, well, for everybody.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
Now, I'm in an ethnic neighborhood, right?

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
So, and the mayor is Italian, mayor of Atlanta.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Well, his mother used to come down from up the hill.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
And she would come down and she would book the numbers.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
Not every day. Some people did it every day.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
But she booked it every so often.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
And then, you know, walk back up the hill and stuff.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And a lot of the people booked numbers with my mother

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
or my father also booked it at the plant.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:52.000
And so, and then Trippi, who was this tall white guy,

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Trippi was the runner.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:58.000
So he would bring in the slips. He would take the money, you know.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
And I think people felt comfortable doing it with my mother

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.000
because she was honest as hell, you know, as was my father.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Now, my sister told me that my father once got arrested

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:15.000
for and had the number of slips on him.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
And my sister said she was so embarrassed

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
because it was in the Tarry Town Daily News.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Yes. And now, what was funny about that was

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
everybody booked with my father.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
So somebody must have wanted something,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
somebody didn't get a pay off, something.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Because it was like the Italian folk, the Irish folk,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:36.000
the Italian Irish Polish folk, everybody booked with my father.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:37.000
You know, so...

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
Now, the number is...

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:45.000
I just found out recently that it was otherwise known as the...

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:49.000
What are these? The Italian lottery.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:53.000
So if you look it up, and some people suggested it came in

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
through the Italian immigrants who first come in.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
But so it is otherwise known as that.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
But the numbers were based...

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
The ones I knew were based on the race.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
And certain races that were being played that day, that day.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.000
And so it was a three-digit number.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:13.000
You could combine it, you could do, you know, four, five, three, three, five, four, you know, however.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
And it was called boxing it.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:20.000
And it was simple enough so that people could understand it.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.000
But I didn't quite get all of the stuff around it.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
I just knew it was based on that day's race.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
You know, which in that day's race.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.000
And that people would then come to collect, you know, if they won the numbers.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
And...

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:39.000
So, and then, you know, my mother would get a cut off whatever,

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:42.000
particularly if somebody won who had bet with her.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
And then people would tip you and, you know, all of a sudden.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
One time my mother bet.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
And I always remember this because she told me this story.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:54.000
She said, she won. And she then called my aunt Helen, her sister, who lived in the Bronx.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:59.000
They were close. I mean, they were so close that every day I would call my aunt Helen,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
only for four, four, nine, eight, six.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
I would call her every night because my mother would say, call Helen.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
And I'd go, okay, close, close.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
My mother wins.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:12.000
And she then calls my aunt Helen and says, Helen, get ready. I'm going to pick you up.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
We're going to go buy some fur coats.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:20.000
So she and my mother got these fur coats from whatever my mother had played in one.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
So, yeah.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:28.000
What kind of work did your mother do after your father died?

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:31.000
Well, you know, I mean, it was great, first of all, when my father died.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
Now, they're hearing your questions, right?

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
Okay, fine.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:38.000
When after he died, what was great about the unions, of course,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
is that they were pensions for the family.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:46.000
So my mother has a modicum of, you know, a small amount,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
but she also knows she has to work.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
Oh, let me, isn't that fact?

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.000
Let me tell you what she does with that small amount of money,

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:59.000
because she realized she needed a car.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And so she was going to buy a car and, you know, pay for it over time.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:10.000
The only one of the two times that I had ever seen my mother talk about race

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:14.000
was this time when she goes to buy a car, it was going to be a valiant.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:20.000
And she buys this, she goes and comes back and she is huffing man.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:24.000
Because the man is obviously, the white salesman has obviously disrespected her

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:28.000
and suggested that she does not have the money to buy this.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:33.000
She comes back, she takes all of the money out that would,

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:38.000
for the, not just the down payment, but to pay for the car outright

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:41.000
and gives it to the man.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:46.000
So that, you know, it was an inroad and whatever might have been there.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:50.000
But that money was there because, you know, they didn't spend much money on stuff.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
But also because, you know, there was a UAW pension that just went to her.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
However, that wasn't enough.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:00.000
And so she then gets a job.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Oh, well, first of all, she goes for, you had to get on a list.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:05.000
So you had to take an exam.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.000
Now my mother was very smart.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:12.000
She had an eighth grade education, but she was really smart and corrected my grammar.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:17.000
Because, I mean, I would say, well, he went with Henry and me.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:22.000
She said, no, with Henry and I, she said me, Henry and me.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:23.000
She always is the preposition.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.000
She knew the parts of the, you know, it was all of that.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:31.000
So even to my, even now, I correct my grammar based on my mother standing over my shoulder, right?

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:36.000
But so she knew all this stuff, but she kept getting low marks.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:42.000
And you had to be in the top whatever number to be considered for a county job.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:49.000
She goes to Mr. Slaven who ran the drugstore and says to Mr. Slaven, you know, I can't seem to get hired.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:53.000
She said, it seems to me that I'm coming up at the top of the exam.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:56.000
But nobody's calling me for work.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:59.000
He says, Mr. Slaven says, how are you registered?

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
And she says, Democrat.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.000
You got to change your registration.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
Be a Republican.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:09.000
And she does, and I always remember this, immediately.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.000
She gets called.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:17.000
And so then she becomes a county worker as a secretary at the county office building in White Plains.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
So she's doing that every day.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:23.000
You said one or one or two times, you're not going to talk to them?

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Oh, good pick up.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Yes.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:26.000
Which I would not have remembered.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:27.000
So thank you.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:39.000
The other time was when she mentioned going to see Birth of a Nation in whatever that would have been 1915 or something during President Wilson's presidency.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:46.000
And she said that she went in and for those who don't know, the birth of a nation was based on the book.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
Should I go through all that?

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:49.000
Yeah.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:50.000
Okay.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Based on a book written by Klansman.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:53.000
It valorized the clan.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:59.000
And just said, you know, basically they were the protectors of White womanhood after reconstruction.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
And that's the reason why people were safe in the South.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:02.000
Okay.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:06.000
So, and they absolutely make horrible.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:14.000
They make the, it's the whole cool thing and ignorant and rapist as the former enslaved people.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:24.000
So, and, but what film courses do with this film is that they really teach it as for the technique because it was a new technique.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:27.000
And sometimes they don't even mention how racist it was.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:28.000
Okay.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
So, I've gone to film departments.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
And, okay, so I know about this.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.000
But the, what she remembered was that she had gone with a friend of hers.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:43.000
And she said she saw the way the black people were portrayed.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
And by the way, I should mention that, well, I'm sorry.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
The way they were portrayed.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:51.000
And she said, I couldn't even lift my head.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:55.000
She said, we came out of that theater and all I could do was look down at the pavement.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
I was so ashamed.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.000
Never talked about the larger issue of racism or any of that.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:02.000
That was the incident.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:03.000
That's what I learned.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Now, I later find out when we're doing eyes on the prize.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
And I mentioned to John Dindmer.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:18.000
I said, you know, I saw this when I was the only black person in my AP history course at Sleepy Hollow High School.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
And I loved the course.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:23.000
But we were doing something on reconstruction.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:28.000
And I said the only, of course it was, I mean, just a short piece on reconstruction.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
But it was so negatively portrayed.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:38.000
And in fact, the only illustration was the one that came from birth of a nation,

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.000
which I find out.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.000
But I didn't know what that was.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:47.000
I just knew it was an illustration and it showed what was supposed to be a white scala wag.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And they were, the black eye was disheveled and he had his feet on the desk of the,

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:57.000
what was supposed to be the state legislature during reconstruction.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And you see the white guy who's come down from the north and he looks horrible, you know.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And the whole framing of it was as a really negative thing.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:16.000
So you didn't get anything about South Carolina, you know, first time you get free public education for poor whites as well as black people, you know, all that.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:20.000
So I mentioned to its eyes on the prize school.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:25.000
It's say, eyes one would have been somewhere around mid 80s.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:30.000
And one of our advisors was John Dindmer, who does local people, right? But hadn't done it yet.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:40.000
And so I say to John, you know, John, I remember this book and it had this illustration in it of what was supposed to be black reconstruction.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And I said, when we looked at it and you saw that horrible caricature, all I remember is the white kids in my class kind of looking back at me, you know, kind of trying not to look but always looking back.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:03.000
And I felt really ashamed. I mean, as my mother had with the same, you know, semi same imagery, that's it.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:11.000
So I say so and the thing is what they were denied was the same thing I was denied, which was the reality of what black reconstruction really was.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And the sense that I got coming out of that, which was this is what happens when black people are put into any position of authority or control.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:33.000
Right. So I get that message, oh my god, classmates get that. And that's so I asked John, John Dindmer, what am I remembering this? And he said, oh yeah, that was and he remembered the authors.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:37.000
And he said that was a nationally prescribed textbook at the time.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:48.000
So other people are getting this, you know, so anyway, I can't remember how I started out. Oh, because that's it. So that's that's the other part of that was that imagery.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:28:00.000
So it's never just a film. People will tell me, why are you getting soft set like with Mississippi burning? Why are you getting soft set? It's just a film. It's never just a film. You know, so yeah.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:09.000
So you covered a lot of different things about the only thing I remember talking once and you telling me the letter to the editor about the little last thing.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:12.000
Yes, I did. I forgot that. Yes.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:21.000
So I'm in high school. So somewhere between 10th grade and 12th grade. So wait, 57. Okay. So 57, 44. What is that 13?

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:24.000
I do. It's just something here. Okay.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:36.000
And I remember writing a letter, which was to tell the Tarotan Daily News, I don't know why these students in Little Rock are trying to get into this white school.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:44.000
They're better off just pursuing their education however they want because it's really about education and we will progress through that.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.000
So how far we've come?

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:54.000
Yes, exactly. That's right. That's exactly. That's right. Yeah.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:29:08.000
Yeah. So it was, you know, I mean, until I get to sneak. It could have been my mother. You know, it could have been, but I should not blame my mother for this.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:23.000
It could have been other folks in the school. I mean, since that's what I got when I'm at Swarthmore, good Quaker College, when we're doing the desegregating and good Quaker children is saying to us, you'd be better off not doing any demonstrating, but staying on campus.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:34.000
And just pursuing your education as one of the students said to somebody else, they would be better doing that because they'll be, oh, no, how did he put it?

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:48.000
Because they will be able to contribute more to their race. That was the thing. Yes. So I mean, that was the general line of thinking of most people, most white people and some black people too, but most white people.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:54.000
So I can see that I would have incorporated that, you know, given that I'm sitting there. Yeah.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:59.000
Do you have anyone that's looking up and compare how much you've contributed and who's contributed?

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:03.000
Oh, that one. No. No, forget him. Exactly.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:13.000
So let's jump ahead and you just mentioned you go to college at Swarthmore. So how do you end up at Swarthmore and what's it like?

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:31.000
I was one of eight black students who come into Swarthmore that year. So that was 62. Now, I was in the top three. I mean, there were three of us who were in the top as we graduated, had small graduating class.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:36.000
And I applied to Bennington where my sister had gone.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:48.000
Brinmore, I think, Adiach and Swarthmore. And Bennington actually, because my sister had not done that well at Bennington.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:59.000
And so Bennington says, well, we can, we will admit you, but we're not going to give you the money that we understand Swarthmore is giving and that we understand they really are going to be doing.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:09.000
However, they said this in their letter. You got it. And then I get the Swarthmore letter and the Swarthmore letter says full freight for four years. Now my mother obviously had no money.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:17.000
So I'm thinking, oh, okay, I guess I'll do Swarthmore. So I come in as one of eight four boys, four black kids.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
This is all incoming freshman class.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Four black men, four black women. I assumed it was so that we would not have to date outside our little group. All of eight of us.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:34.000
Oh, yeah, immediately. Yeah, of course.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:41.000
But the main thing was that we were also all housed with Quaker children.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:46.000
And the assumption being, I think, that the Quaker children would be more accepting of us. Right.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:50.000
So I got made, who was, I can't remember, makes last name.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:55.000
Let me just say that was not automatically true once we started doing demonstrations.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:05.000
But when we come in, it's eight and it's four and four. And when I come in, there are maybe two other black students there.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:13.000
One was a senior and one was a sophomore to my remember, at least my memory. That's what I've got.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:19.000
Somebody when I said this, we had an all day meeting when we did our hands on the Freedom Plow all day at Swarthmore.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:26.000
And I think the president or somebody may have said they thought there was a third and that that was an African student.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:30.000
But I'm not sure because I've never checked the records.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:38.000
Anyway, so we come in and I had been, you know, I mean, a senior year always is, you know, you've been sliding through.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:41.000
I come into Swarthmore and it's like, oh my god.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:49.000
And not only is it academically really pressurized, but it's also that most of these kids have come out of, you know, Sidwell Friends.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:58.000
I mean Quaker schools come out of private schools, you know, which now are called independent schools.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:06.000
I'm coming from a good public high school, but they've also come from families where they wintered in Paris, you know.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:13.000
And I had been to Albany, you know, that was New York, New York, excuse me, Albany, New York.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.000
And that was my one and only plane ride before this.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:21.000
And that was only because I was part of the all-state youth orchestra, which went to, or was that Buffalo?

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.000
We went to Buffalo. Sorry, Buffalo.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:32.000
So, you know, these were worldly young kids, which was why I was so amazed when we did the demonstrations and they turned against us.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
But some of them, not all of them.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:47.000
So anyway, so I come in and, you know, and I'm, as usual, very good in English, but it's like even Paulie Psy, which was an 8 a.m. on a Saturday course, with a professor who was phoning it in.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:50.000
You know, it's like, and I'm, you know, I'm not a morning person.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:54.000
8 a.m. on a Saturday, and it's like he's reading from his notes, please.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:34:08.000
But it was in that Paulie Psy class that I got to respect this one young guy who knew about Lenin and Trotsky and all this stuff that I had never heard of before.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:16.000
He's the one who says, I overhear him saying once we do the demonstrations, you know, they'd be better off sticking to education.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:23.000
Oh, yeah. They're my little theorist who I just thought was so amazing because he knew all this stuff, right?

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:27.000
Yes, because they'll be a better credit. They'll be able to do more for their race. Yes.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:35.000
Were you aware of the sitting in the Freedom Rage before you go to college?

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:45.000
I was not, and that's so surprising to me. You know, it's like I probably even knew maybe Emmett Till, but I don't remember it because I'm sure for given my mother,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:55.000
although we had a weekly subscription to Jet Magazine, but I don't remember seeing that then, unless I just blocked it out, or she made sure I didn't see that issue.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:59.000
I don't know because I do remember reading the jet.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:05.000
It did, but I don't remember any of that.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:12.000
So, I don't remember any stuff, you know.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:22.000
And then I get, so that's why I'm not really sure what really would draw us me to the SDS meeting, but I don't know if you want to get to that yet.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:25.000
So, how? So, you're in your first year at Swarthmore?

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.000
Yeah. And you end up at a SDS meeting?

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:34.000
Yes. And the SDS chapter was called SPAC, the Swarthmore Political Action Committee.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:40.000
And the co-chairs were that, of that, were Mimi Fine Gold and Carl Whitman.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:53.000
Now, Mimi, I did not know until 2010 when I go back to Swarthmore for this all day, hands on the Freedom Plow Meeting conference, whatever event.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:58.000
And I go back and I decide I need to look up who Mimi was.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:07.000
And I found out that she had done six weeks in parchment prison on the Freedom Rides before she comes back to be co-chair of SPAC.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:11.000
Didn't know that. When I'm looking at her, I knew nothing about her background.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:14.000
So, she was a core person, she was on core staff.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:19.000
She later goes into Placaman County, deadly Placaman County, Louisiana.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:27.000
Didn't know any of that. But mainly, I did not know that she had done the six weeks in parchment before I see her standing up at a SPAC meeting.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:35.000
Her co-chair, Carl Whitman, later after he leaves Swarthmore, they get married.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:41.000
That didn't work out too well. He was gay. And then he then becomes big in the gay rights movement.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:44.000
And he does this big treatise that people use.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:52.000
So, it's like they were leaders then. And at this point, they were really doing a lot around...

00:36:52.000 --> 00:37:05.000
SPAC had three main things. One was organizing the all black cafeteria staff for better working conditions, better pay, health conditions, all that stuff.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:12.000
And then I'll get back to that. Second was doing tutorials in Chester, Pennsylvania, which is still has the PITS school.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:17.000
Just horrible, primarily black schools. So, they were doing tutorials.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:37.000
And then the third thing was doing helping Gloria Richardson and CNAC, the Cambridge Nonviolent Action Committee, a SNCC affiliate, with opening up the all the segregated public facilities.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:43.000
Cambridge Black folks had had the votes since the 40s, but now they were opening up the trying to desegregate the public facilities.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:51.000
So, it was those three things. It was the black cafeteria staff and the tutorial in Chester, Pennsylvania and Cambridge, Maryland.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:38:02.000
So, all black cafeteria staff, I'm work study. So, it's hard for young people to understand what something like Swarthmore was like.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:14.000
I mean, it was gorgeous. Still gorgeous. So, the dining hall with this gorgeous dining hall with these big old wooden tables, and we all sat around it, and we were served.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:24.000
Nobody had to bust their own tables. You never thought of that, right? So, the waitresses would come in, and they would not only serve you, but they would take the stuff back.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:41.000
The place back, well, I was one of the waitresses in the evening. I think maybe two or three nights, because I was work study, you know, as part of my four-year vol, you know, tuition paid.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:58.000
So, one of the things that the black cafeteria staff had been trying to get was covering on this open, it was a big hot water pipe that was right on one of the walls.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:12.000
And so, they would, in the rush to go back and forth in the dining hall, they would sometimes back into it, and they would get cinched on their leg.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:24.000
Swarthmore never did anything about it, right? So, that was one of the grievances they had. Okay, I'm moving back and forth. I hit it.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:42.000
And I swear to God, I had H2O backwards on my inner thigh. Oh, yeah, four years. Oh, it was amazing. Now, of course, the college is really worried about me. So, when it happens, I remember Mimi saying, you got it, I'm a student.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:55.000
And I don't have to worry about whether I sue them, because I'm not working. You know, it's like, okay, so I remember Mimi saying to me, we've got to figure out, I mean, she was really concerned that I was okay. I mean, there was that.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:40:05.000
But the other thing was, how can we use this to open up stuff for the rest of the really working, you know, cafeteria staff? So, I remember being called into some...

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:16.000
I'm sorry, I'm sorry, I should have mentioned that before, because it's how I get there. But anyway, yes, and I'll go back to how I get there.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:28.000
So, she says, this is what we're going for, and there was this wonderful woman whose name I can't remember from the black cafeteria staff, it's like I'm doing trays.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:39.000
And she would come to our meetings, and she often brought some other black, usually female workers, because I think it might have been all female.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:44.000
I don't know who was in the kitchen, but in terms of the weight staff, I'm pretty sure it was all black female.

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:56.000
Anyway, she was amazing, because I had in one of my old iris, I had that she had, you know, she was coming in how amazing she was and just, you know, and just smart as a whip, you know, it's just...

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:09.000
So, anyway, so I remember being called into some administrative office, the Deans of Somebody, who is clearly very nervous about the fact that I have gotten, you know, this thing.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:22.000
Yes, this injury, and they want to know what I'd want, and so I have been schooled by Mimi about, you know, well, this is what we need, and if I remember correctly, we got some of it.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:28.000
But it was also because this weight staff really was strong. I mean, they were really amazing and stuff.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:38.000
And, you know, I'm sure Swarthmore was aware of its quaker, you know, heritage, and, you know, it looked bad.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:43.000
Little pressure. Little pressure. That's right, exactly. Yes, that's it.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:51.000
And so, but the reason I first start going to the meetings is that it really is because, you know, I sometimes say it's because my mother's not there to stop me.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:57.000
I'm sampling everything. I'm a freshman, it's like, what can I get into, what's going on, you know, it's tough.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:06.000
So, I happen to... I don't know who told me about it, but somebody mentions it, or I see a leaflet, and I said, let me just try this, you know.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:11.000
And I get deeper and deeper into it. That's the thing. I have no idea what you're always me.

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:23.000
But for the first time, I see somebody actually protesting some of this stuff. You know, I mean, it's like, I think in the back of my mind, I always knew there were things going on.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:30.000
But it's not something my mother would raise. It's not something I was talking about when I was at Tarrytown, but...

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:38.000
And maybe it was cumulative. You know, finally, at this point, you know, it's 62-63. Maybe I'm actually waking up to some of the racial stuff. I don't know.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:47.000
But I go to this thing, and they are so amazing to me. I mean, Mimi was just amazing. Carl somewhat, but it was Mimi who I really...

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:51.000
Because she was just energetic, and you know, it was amazing.

00:42:51.000 --> 00:43:02.000
So, you know, we do whatever we do with them. But anyway, so I go to this meeting, I find out what their agenda, you know, what programs are working on.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:12.000
And then, through them, I go to the... That first bus ride going down to Cambridge, Maryland. So I sign up for the bus ride.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:13.000
Is this what we call?

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:20.000
And so, weekend. That's right. Because the guarantee was that you would go down on a Saturday, and you would come back Sunday night.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:29.000
And you would do picket lines. And the guarantee was that you would come back Sunday night, so you would be there for Monday classes.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:34.000
And this is going to Cambridge, Maryland, which I think was maybe about two and a half hours away.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:43.000
And we're smart, more students doing like how are students doing the burden student money and for supporting movement with buses and rollercoats?

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:51.000
Oh, that's interesting. I don't know. You know, because I really am new. So I don't really know what Mimi was doing. I just get on the bus. That's exactly it. I get on the bus.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:57.000
And we were one of many colleges from the area who were going down.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:05.000
So you would get there and it wouldn't just be Swarthmore College students. It would be... Because I remember Mark Suckle, who later goes down into the National Office.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:15.000
He's coming from someplace. You would see Morgan State folk. And I don't remember the Howard people, but I remember some of the other nearby.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:18.000
Galture, I remember, was coming down.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:21.000
So this is spring fall?

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:27.000
No, oh, I see. Okay, I get in. So it would be fall. Probably late fall.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
62. That's right. Yeah.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:36.000
And what was it like to go to Cambridge and participate in the picket?

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:40.000
I have certain memories. And so that's really it.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:46.000
What I remember is the first... One of the first demonstrations. I'm not sure if it was the first.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:51.000
I remember we were trying to integrate the chop tank in.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:57.000
And I remember being enough close that I could see inside the end.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:04.000
And it was at Old Barn Grill. It was dirty. It was dank. It smelled... I always say I've brought Galture liquor.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:06.000
I mean, it's just nasty.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:10.000
And I'm thinking, why am I trying to get in here?

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:12.000
It's like this is a nasty place.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:16.000
No, exactly. Under normal circumstances. Yes, okay.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:21.000
But it was like, I see this big, burly white guy. Who's telling me, I can't come in.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:25.000
Close on black. And I see him. And it's like, you're telling me.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:33.000
I can't, you know, it was stupid. So at a certain point, we start getting arrested.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:36.000
No, right.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:41.000
Well, in many ways I did, but with this thing, no, it was clear. That was clear.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:49.000
So I then, either there or we were also trying to integrate the skating rink.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:56.000
Which, you know, in everybody, I skated at that. And it was our roller, and it was a roller rink too.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
Is that in Cambridge?

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:02.000
In Cambridge, right in Cambridge. And that was the source of it initially.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:09.000
Because the reason Gloria Richardson, who is at that point, the overleader.

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:17.000
I mean, she's the one who most of the media knows. But as she often said, this was a, you know, this was group leadership in Cambridge.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:21.000
And so there were a lot of people who were part of the main committee and stuff.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:30.000
But Gloria, it's her daughter and the young people in Cambridge who decide they want to integrate the roller.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:37.000
I used to know the name of it, but the rink, the skating rink.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:45.000
And so Gloria and one of her maybe relatives, it might have been her cousin and laws, a matter of fact.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:52.000
But in any event, the two women go down to SNCC. Because they decide they need help in terms of how to organize demonstrations.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:56.000
And Gloria said, you know, she put on little white glows and they had heels and stuff.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:02.000
And of course they walk into the national divorce, the physical and everybody's and jeans and overalls, you know, stuff. But they had their little gloves.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:12.000
And so Ku Klits sent as a SNCC field secretary, is Reggie Robinson. And he's the one I first meet as a SNCC person when I go in.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:23.000
But the reason they choose the roller rink is because it's the young people. And Gloria said, you know, it was her daughter who said, you know, we're tired of this.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:29.000
And but the older people knew we don't know how to quite do this. We don't want the young people going crazy.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:35.000
And so we need to figure out how to organize this. But also Gloria was, you know, her family was well known.

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:42.000
Both among the black people and the white people. And so, you know, she and her family had the drugstore.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:49.000
They had various businesses. Pop Herb, whom I stayed with overnight when I would come down. Pop Herb was the funeral parlor.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:58.000
So, what did a lot of people do? I remember a lot of people. But that it went off and on. You know, it wasn't always that.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:04.000
But in terms of Pop Herb and as the funeral director, he would put a bail for us.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:16.000
There would be people who would stay in his attic, because our members staying there. Mark, I remember was there. There were other people, you know, we would, how we would be housed up there.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:21.000
And yeah. So, yeah.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:25.000
And you said, Reggie Robinson was the first Nickerson unit.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:26.000
Yeah.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:34.000
And Gloria is the visible leader in Cambridge. Do you remember what your impressions were of them?

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:39.000
Yes. And before I forget what I meant to say before I got into who was, who was staying there.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:48.000
One of the things that was clear with Gloria, and we can get into this later, but I want to, well, I'm thinking about it, was that she was never philosophically nonviolent.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:57.000
And in fact, she said when her daughter said, you know, when she's bringing people in and stuff, her daughter says specifically to Gloria,

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:01.000
you can't come on the picket line because you're going to hit somebody.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:13.000
And Gloria said she knew that was true. And it said, I'm sorry, and it said in fact that one time she said, she saw white guys whom she knew.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:24.000
She said, I knew these guys. I grew up here. They grew up here. They're calling me name. She said so when the picket line ended, when one of, when they started leaving, she said, I tripped one of them.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:29.000
So that was Gloria. Yeah. It was not only that she wasn't philosophically nonviolent.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:35.000
She wasn't even tactically nonviolent. No, except on the line. She understood that on the line, I will be tactically.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:50.000
But her main thing was when the demonstrations are gone, all bets are off. And she said if they come on our side of race street, because race street was a dividing line between white and black and Cambridge, Maryland, she said, I can't guarantee one way or the other. They're safety.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:50:08.000
Yeah. Yeah. And Cambridge, of course, became kind of notorious for some of the battles. Yes. But you were there for that. I was not there for that. And I resent. I sometimes resent the way the history says it, which is, you know, it's when Stokeley goes in that suddenly or rap goes in that suddenly everything goes.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:27.000
Those people were never philosophically nonviolent. You know, and so yeah. They were always protecting the black community when the white took come on rampage. Yes. That's correct. They were like Birmingham on Birmingham Hill. Same thing, which was the black community protected its community.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:42.000
If you come in here and so Cambridge did the same thing when people when the white vigilantes, the white domestic terrorists came through, then you would find that black people and white people knew that that black people did have their guns and they would shoot them. I mean shoot at them.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:54.000
So you said that you're trying things out because you're away from home and do you remember how you felt participating in the cities?

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:04.000
I felt amazing. I mean, I really did. I felt it was such energy to me to be part of, I mean, part of, if I had done it by myself, it would be one thing.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:22.000
But it was like I was part of this group, the young people who were my age. And a lot of them were black. I mean, that was the thing when I get into SNCC. Well, anyway, a lot of them are, you know, are doing something about the stuff that I have sublimated all of my life in Tarotan.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:43.000
I mean, I knew black people couldn't move anywhere on the other, on Broadway or the other side of it. I knew that. But it was a given. I knew that I didn't see any black businesses. I didn't see this. I didn't see anything in terms of Tarotan, aside from my father and other people, you know, going to the plant.

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:58.000
There were no black, there was no black middle class in Tarotan. The one time we got somebody who actually had money was when Chris Cowlowe, a cab Cowlowe's daughter came in and she was in our senior class.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:04.000
Or maybe our junior class because she didn't last long. They eventually moved her to a private school, I think.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:18.000
But that was the first time I saw anybody who was middle class. So even seeing people who are running their own businesses as I saw on Cambridge and other black communities in the South, I didn't see any of that in Tarotan.

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:39.000
So this was amazing. First of all, I see black young people and white young people who are fighting this thing. We are so tight. The camaraderie is so amazing. I'm going to these mass meetings where people are singing these freedom scongs and it's like you lift up to another place.

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:56.000
I'm not religious. My mother read the Bible every Sunday but she hated organized religions. I never went to church except once we can mention. Well, let me just divert. I start going to the Baptist church, the white Baptist church in Tarotan.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:15.000
I didn't last long. I go one summer and I think I came through maybe the camp. It might have started that way. My mother was very pleased because even though she could not handle organized religion for whatever reason, she never mentioned it, she was pleased that I was going to church.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:32.000
Yes, that's what it was. It was Bible camp because it must have been because I remember I got a dollar for memorizing the books of the Bible. Genesis, Exodus, the Loviticus, the number of Sodoron, the Jewish Jewish Jewish Ruth. First and second Samuels, first and second Kings.

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:51.000
Yes, well, that was the only way I could remember it. That's exactly it. Yes, but I got this dollar. My mother was very pleased and I didn't. Anyway, but then I overheard some of the, because it was all white, I think I was the only black child.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:54:09.000
Yes, and I hear some of the white people in the church. I don't know. I happened to just overhear this and I hear them saying that we have to be, they say, we have to be careful because we don't want too many black kids coming in because then we'll get overrun.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:17.000
That was the last time I ever went to camp, I never went to church, my mother never said anything. That was it.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:31.000
So now I'm now in Cambridge. It's this mass meeting, it's a black church and it's like, oh, okay, you know, because it's the songs. It's the songs and what they're preaching about, of course, is freedom and liberation.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:43.000
I mean, it's all that stuff. So I get, you know, so when I go back to Swarthmore each Monday and then it becomes maybe each Sunday, then sometimes it becomes Monday because we get held over.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:54.000
Then, well, when I go back, I'm taking all this back with me to campus, you know, and that energy I'll take him back with me.

00:54:54.000 --> 00:55:10.000
So you're getting increased in the community with the protest, the demonstration related to campus and Cambridge.

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:20.000
And let me show you, I know you decide to take a year off school.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:33.000
Okay, well, Penny Patch, who had been in her sophomore year, white student, she had gone down to Southwest Georgia.

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:38.000
And I had heard about her, but she was not when I first come in that first semester.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:43.000
Second semester, she returns from all of any Georgia and the SNCC project.

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:51.000
And she hears that I've been from the SPAC people, that I have been going to the meetings. And so she comes into my dorm room.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:56:05.000
And she said, look, I hear that, you know, you've been going to the meetings and the demonstrations. And, you know, you might want to think about taking off the next semester, which would have been the first semester of my sophomore year.

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:09.000
And working full-time with SNCC and Cambridge, Maryland.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:17.000
And so, you know, I start thinking, she said, however, if you do decide to do this, you've got to apply, because I'm coming from the North.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:24.000
If I were Sagan and Black, you know, wouldn't have been a problem. But so she says, if you do decide to do this, though, you've got to go buy Ruby Dars.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:33.000
And that's what she meant. Ruby Dars, Smith Robinson, the amazing administrator in the National Office and Atlanta.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:48.000
So I didn't know anything about Ruby Dars then. So I say, okay, well, let me see what happens, you know. So I think I went ahead and applied and then got confirmation that I have been accepted for this next, you know, for the...

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:51.000
And you're specifically applying to work in Kansas.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:52.000
Yes.

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:56.000
And so you're going to live with the Richardson family, not your kin.

00:56:56.000 --> 00:57:01.000
And actually, probably not that. I'm probably pop her because that's where I used to say, yeah.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:12.000
And she's... So I get that I've been allowed to do this. And because I got back from SNCC that there's confirmation.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:17.000
And so now the point is, how do I tell my mother that I'm thinking about doing this, right?

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:30.000
So I go to the hall phone because of course it's before cell phones, right? And I go to the hall phone and I call my mother and I tell her, you know, I frame it in the sense which I had done.

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:39.000
I contacted the administration. I was guaranteed that I was going to maintain my full four-year scholarship. Nothing would change.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:43.000
I could come back in again. They were kind. They were cool with it.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:49.000
So I tell her all this. And to me, she was amazingly calm. She asked some questions.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:57.000
But then I hang up and I go back to my dorm room and I'm thinking, I'm over. I've made it through this. And I had been so worried about it, right?

00:57:57.000 --> 00:58:06.000
I don't make it more than I... In my mind, I'm thinking 20 to 30 minutes. And I get call back to the hall phone. Somebody picked it up.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:16.000
It calls me. I get to the phone and it is my older sister, nine years older than me, Carita, when we call Kita. And she is screaming at me over the phone.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:25.000
Like, what are you thinking of? You can't do this. And at that point, I think she was working for Columbia Records in the A&R division in New York City.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:32.000
And she said, you know, her main thing was you can't sacrifice your education for this.

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:42.000
But then somehow I convinced her. And I told her, I really have guaranteed that, you know, coming back, it's going to be okay. And somehow convinced her.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:58.000
And so everybody's agreed. I can do this now. So I finished out, you know, the rest of that year. And then I had already accepted to do... To be a student, not intern, but a student worker at the nearby kind of halfway house.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:12.000
It was for foster kids. And so as a counselor, student counselor there, that's how I made my money. I wanted to not do it. But then the person who had hired me had said, look, you know, it's too late for me to get somebody else now.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:24.000
So I made it through that. And then I took the bus, you know, in the fall, September. And no, it was October, because I remember I still had the stub bus trip.

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:38.000
And I went down and went to Cambridge. But before I tell you that, I should say, because it reminds me of my mother driving me with my sister down to Swarthmore that first time.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:50.000
And she had never gone to Bennington. But I could see through her eyes that this was just amazing. You know, I mean, this was...

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:59.000
She had no sense of what Swarthmore meant, that it was an illegal. She had no sense of that. But she did have a sense that this was prestigious.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:11.000
You know, rolling hills. And they let me drive. Now, had I known how I... I mean, if I had been them, I would never have allowed me to drive.

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:21.000
Because, you know, at that point, I was... I've always driven fast. But I was, you know, 18, 19 years old at that point.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:34.000
And I remember driving through the... either the Holland or the Lincoln tunnel. And at some point, I changed lanes. And I remember my sister saying, no, you can't change lanes on the time.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:46.000
And I'm still... Okay, you know, so we get down there. And my sister was absolutely wonderful, because my sister could talk to anybody. I was very...

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:55.000
You know, I was shy in my own way. I mean, I didn't know how to deal with strangers. I worried about talking to people. And said, my sister didn't worry about any of that.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:01:05.000
So she could talk to anybody, anywhere, whoever they were. So she talks to everybody in the dorm. She gets to me. She introduces me. This is my sister. You know, she's...

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:15.000
May comes in. My sister was the life of a party wherever she was. So I feel easier, because she has kind of paved the way for me.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:27.000
And my mother, you know, my poor mother, because see, my sister left. So it was really my mother and I growing up for those last years.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:35.000
And, you know, I was the baby. And it's like, you know, we were like this with my mother. And I...

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:44.000
I don't know how she made it. You know, for me it was like, oh, I'm in the strange world. And, you know, but she's gone back to an empty house. And I think about that now. You know, it just...

01:01:44.000 --> 01:02:04.000
It must have been hard. Yeah. So anyway, so she goes back with Keeta and my sister, Carita, and, you know, and I'm there. And then, you know, get in. And during the school year, SPAC organizes not only this other stuff, but they decide to run a slate for the...

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:12.000
June, the May Queen. We did a May ceremony. That's right. It was the May Queen. And so it used...

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:22.000
It usually was, you know, the girlfriend of the football players. Or... No, no, not football, because they did outlaw football at that point.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:31.000
Fract, all the Fract boys. Okay. So it was somebody's girlfriend. It was a sorority, sweetheart. It was somebody. But it would split the vote.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:46.000
Well, with us, we ran a slate, the SDS slate. And we all block-voted. Right. So Mimi, head of SDS, you know, just got out of parchment, becomes the May Queen.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:55.000
And I become one of the princesses, because that's what we were. And we had a little crown of little roses and stuff.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:05.000
My mother comes down for it. She is so proud. She does not know that a number of the Fract boys and stuff are boycotting the ceremony.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:15.000
She doesn't know that some of the people on the newspaper have mentioned... Have really, first of all, been absolutely death on our demonstrations.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:32.000
And there are editorial policy and some of the reporting, including from one of the people, Elsa, Elsa, who was 16 when she comes on campus, was a friend of mine, had a total photographic memory. She was on my whole.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:39.000
See, let me just go back and say, the demonstrations really split the campus. And so...

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:49.000
These are demonstrations on campus. No. That is correct. So these are the demonstrations in Cambridge, Maryland.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:59.000
And these are the demonstrations where I hear this person from my polypsychlas, who says, you know, these black students would be better off doing...

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:05.000
He is part of a group of folks who normally liberal, I thought.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:16.000
And so that is really coming out in the newspaper, in comments, because they are interviewing students who are saying again, the Negro students would be better off concentrating on their education.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:19.000
That is right.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:27.000
So when it gets to the point where... And we are getting arrested, you know, and all that stuff.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:33.000
But now it is getting to the May Queen and we have taken over the ceremony, you know.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:40.000
So a number of them don't come. Of course all of the kind of progressive kids come and we do this.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:47.000
But the main thing is I am thinking about my mother. And she is just proud that she can be that there is her daughter with her little, you know, the roses and the...

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:59.000
And I introduce her to everybody. And you know, she had remembered it from being down there. But it is like, my mother was not traveled, you know.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:07.000
And so she had gotten on the train, come down to, you know, buy herself. And she was just going to the city into New York. But she knew the city.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:13.000
And this was, you know, this was new. And so, yeah, she was very proud.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:16.000
Yes, she gave her a nice memory before you quit school.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:20.000
Yes, exactly. That is right. Yes, it did. And she didn't know that that is what I was going to do. So it was okay.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:28.000
That is right. So anyway. So she goes back, we continue the rest of it.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:39.000
So you mentioned Mimi and how important she is. Mimi Fine Gold. And that she had been on the Freedom Rides in that spring 61, on her 61.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:47.000
And then she is one of the leaders of the SDS chapter over there. She ends up in Louisiana with CORE.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:55.000
Placaman Parish, that is right. And so do you have a sense of sort of how she ends up in CORE and you end up in SNCC for you to go into different directions?

01:05:55.000 --> 01:06:00.000
The thing is, see, when she came back from the Freedom Rides, she was already CORE. When she comes back from Placaman Parish.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:07.000
No, I am sorry. When she comes back from parchment, she is already CORE. I think... Freedom Rides.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:16.000
I think it is the Freedom Rides. I don't know where she first took SDS with CORE. Because she is from Brooklyn. I don't know whether she is doing stuff with Arnie, whatever I can't remember.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:19.000
But the Brooklyn CORE chapter was major.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:25.000
I just find it interesting that you are on the same campus and you end up in the field with different civil rights organizations.

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:31.000
It is accepted. I am coming through Cambridge and she is not necessarily. She is already an activist before we go into Cambridge.

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:33.000
But she is still going to Cambridge. Absolutely.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:35.000
That is not her introduction.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:36.000
That is it.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:42.000
I didn't even know about CORE but she was already that when I see her.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:45.000
No wonder when she goes into the field.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:47.000
Did she go to SNCC?

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:48.000
No.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:53.000
No. I don't know whether... See, I am pretty sure that she continues her... Well, she was a senior.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:07:01.000
So I think she leaves Cambridge. I mean, I am sorry. When she graduates. I am pretty sure that is when she goes into Placaman.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:03.000
County in Louisiana.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:07.000
I have been interested personally just in helping people getting a different...

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:08.000
Yes.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:10.000
Sorry about the distress.

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:11.000
No, no.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:17.000
So you have a commitment to a summer job so you go home and you do your summer job.

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:20.000
Then it is October and you head into Cambridge.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:21.000
Yes.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:24.000
And I continue doing the Cambridge work.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:29.000
But truthfully, I have no real memory except demonstrations.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:30.000
I have no memory of the job.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:31.000
Demonstrations, getting arrested.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:37.000
You know, it wasn't voter registration obviously because they had the voter ready.

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:47.000
So I am pretty sure most of that was demonstrations and organizing around that and getting adult community involved as much as the students.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:52.000
Although they were pretty much already involved adults at that point.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:56.000
So I don't really remember because see, I don't stay that long.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:07:59.000
Because then by...

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:02.000
I go... It is a matter of fact, I hadn't thought about this.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:04.000
I go down in October by November.

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:07.000
I am down in the Atlanta office.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:10.000
Because what happens is that Reggie Robinson says,

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:15.000
look, I am going, I am taking the train to either Cleveland or Cincinnati.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:16.000
I can't remember which.

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:17.000
Cincinnati.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:18.000
Okay.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:21.000
Because what is his name from Arkansas?

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:22.000
Bill Hansen.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:24.000
And what?

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.000
Wait, from Southwest Georgia.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:27.000
Oh God.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:29.000
No, not from South... No, not from South Georgia.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:31.000
It will come to me.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:32.000
They are getting married.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:33.000
Right.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:35.000
And yeah, it will come.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:36.000
Ruthie.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:37.000
Ruthie Harris.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:38.000
No.

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:39.000
Ruthie.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:40.000
Well, Ruthie.

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:42.000
We will leave it at that because I will get totally off.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:46.000
So, Bill Hansen and Ruthie are getting married in...

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:47.000
You said Cincinnati.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:53.000
And Bill Hansen was a Whitefield Secretary working at Arkansas,

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:56.000
which is where Ruthie was from, right.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:59.000
And they are getting married.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:00.000
Reggie knew Bill.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:04.000
And so he says, I am going to take the train from Swarth...

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:05.000
or from Cambridge.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:06.000
Come with me.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:11.000
And on the way back, we will go through the National Office and then come back up again.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:12.000
Okay.

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:14.000
So, we take the train to Ohio.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:16.000
I meet Ruthie.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:20.000
Now, either his or her family was boycotting the...

01:09:20.000 --> 01:09:21.000
because it was interracial.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:22.000
So, Ruthie was black.

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:25.000
Bill was white.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:30.000
I just remember that Ruthie said she had nobody to be her...

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:32.000
her maid of honor.

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:34.000
Now, I had never seen either of these people before.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:37.000
They pour me into some little black dress.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:39.000
They put heels on me.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:42.000
And now, I've been in Gene Scurts all this time.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:44.000
I've been in sneakers, right.

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:48.000
So, I have to fit into this little dress and then walk in these heels.

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:51.000
And I'm the maid of honor for this person I've never met before.

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:53.000
And then we go through the ceremony.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:59.000
And then, on the way back, we get to the National Office.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:05.000
So, I get to this office, which in my mind, I'm thinking is going to be like Urban League.

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:09.000
You know, with rugs on the floor and people dressed in little sluts and stuff.

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:13.000
Well, maybe not the suits, because I mean I had seen what the field workers looked at.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:16.000
But, see, in my mind, I'm thinking also this is a National Office.

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:18.000
So, they're probably dressed differently.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:26.000
So, I get to the office, was it 8 1 1 2 and a half, 6 1 1 1 1 2 and a half rainmasthread, I think.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:29.000
But anyway, 8 1 1 1 2 and a half rainmasthread, which was a side street,

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:31.000
off Hunter.

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:34.000
Not Hunter wrote.

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:37.000
God, what was the main drag that's now Martin Luther King drive?

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:38.000
Are you sure it's not Hunter?

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:40.000
Oh, maybe it is, it's Hunter.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:43.000
Yeah, it's Hunter, which is now Martin Luther King Boulevard.

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:46.000
So, you went down, it was right near the Atlanta University Center,

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:49.000
and you'd go off to the right if you were coming from downtown.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:54.000
And, it was a small street.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:11:00.000
And, it was right next to either Beauty Parlor, I think it was a Beauty Parlor.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:06.000
And, it was like a door, we call it Glass Door.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:11.000
And, I see Reggie get to the door and there's this guy at the top of the stairs,

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:14.000
and he's sweeping the stairs.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:16.000
He's in overalls.

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:23.000
I hear Reggie, you know, hollering and whooping hollering, and either he or the guy says,

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:25.000
hey, Captain, how you doing?

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:28.000
And, they hugged like long last brothers, right?

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:35.000
And, I'm thinking how egalitarian, egalitarian is SNCC because this is the custodian, right?

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:40.000
And, then I find out it's Jim Forman, the executive secretary of the organization,

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:45.000
and he is sweeping as he often did, because it really was a lesson for him.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:51.000
It was everybody in SNCC needed to see him sweeping so that they knew that every job was important.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:55.000
And, yeah, you were supposed to cleave it as clean as you could, the office.

01:11:55.000 --> 01:12:01.000
And, secondly, that no job was too lowly for anybody in the organization to do.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:06.000
So, he would periodically sweep the stairs, not very well, let me just say.

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:07.000
But, he would do it.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.000
Okay.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:15.000
So, then I come up, Reggie says to him, I'm coming from Swarthmore, we're on our way back to Cambridge.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:24.000
Forman finds out that I can take shorthand, which is like, I try and tell people it's kind of like texting, but with symbols.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:27.000
So, everything had a symbol that we did.

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:32.000
And, I knew I had learned this, and could type 90 words a minute.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:41.000
Both of those because, um, Tarrytown Public Schools, when I'm at Washington, Irving, Junior High School, in seventh grade, because I'm black.

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:44.000
And, it really was that, because I was at the top of my class.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:48.000
They shift me into secretarial, assuming that I'm going to do the secretarial route.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:49.000
Okay.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:53.000
Now, at that point, my sister, hello, is at Bennington, but that's okay.

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:57.000
And, so, and also, under the hill, you know, it's, I mean, it's all that stuff.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:02.000
So, my mother makes sure that it's only that year.

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:08.000
She, I do remember her being very upset when she heard that I was being shifted into this.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:15.000
So, I either took the whole semester in the seventh grade or the whole year, either way.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:19.000
I now can type 90 words a minute, and I can take Regshorthand.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:28.000
So, um, they should, and they're older, well, let me not get, okay, so, um, yeah.

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:33.000
And I'll get to Joanne Grant, and my shorthand notes when I'm taking it in SNCC.

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:40.000
But, so, Forman finds this out, and then decides I'm going to be his secretary.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:43.000
So, Regge goes back to Cambridge alone.

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:45.000
So, my trick Cambridge.

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:49.000
I leave my clothes there. I don't remember what happens with the clothes.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:52.000
They probably stay in pop herbs. You know, I don't know what happens.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:14:01.000
And then I go into the Freedom House, which is where the female staff, some of the female staff, from the National Office lived.

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:03.000
But, my first image of-

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:05.000
So, it was fall 63.

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:13.000
That's correct. And the reason I remember it was November was because the first staff meeting I remember was, um, and we had called in,

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:21.000
it wasn't just the Atlanta National Movement staff. It was also the, um, the field staff.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:24.000
And Kennedy had just been shot.

01:14:24.000 --> 01:14:33.000
And so, there's this whole discussion about how we're going to respond to it, particularly given that the federal government hasn't done deadly squat for us and stuff.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:37.000
And I remember Forman saying, you know, we have to be very careful about this.

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:39.000
I remember Dinky crying.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:43.000
Um, Dinky who was, Forman's second-

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:46.000
becomes later on, Forman's second wife.

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:49.000
Um, but I remember her being the only one who was crying, actually.

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:55.000
I'm sure there were others, but most of the people were really trying to figure out how do we respond to this strategically.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:15:00.000
So, um, so yeah, that's how I remember I was there by November.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:03.000
I remember something about that wedding.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:05.000
Hmm.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:07.000
Puffington? Puffington.

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:09.000
Is that Lucy's name?

01:15:09.000 --> 01:15:11.000
I think that might be. I don't remember.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:19.000
I don't know. Um, it seems like I remember you telling me something about that wedding, like, something in a week ago, or something.

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:21.000
Oh, or anything.

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:23.000
No. Okay.

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:25.000
I might have once remembered it, but I don't know.

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:27.000
I don't remember either.

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:29.000
Okay.

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:31.000
So, yeah.

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:35.000
What was, um, what was your job with Forman as Forman's secretary?

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:37.000
Yes.

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:43.000
Well, I'll tell you before I get to that, let me tell you what, when you came into the Atlanta office, okay?

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:48.000
When you first came in, you came up the stairs from the, with the plate, you know, with the window behind you.

01:15:48.000 --> 01:15:54.000
Come up the stairs. If you, you came into the, the kind of reception area.

01:15:54.000 --> 01:16:00.000
And that would have been, um, uh, you would have seen, oh gosh.

01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:04.000
I remember his name before Jimmy Bolton. Thank you.

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:06.000
Yes. Jimmy Bolton was there.

01:16:06.000 --> 01:16:08.000
And he was one of the few guys.

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:12.000
Now, Jimmy was the only person who was overtly gay.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:20.000
I'm sure there were other people, male and female, but he was the only one who, who didn't really try and hide it, you know.

01:16:20.000 --> 01:16:24.000
And then there were other people at the two desks.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:28.000
And Jimmy, by the way, eventually goes off with his mate to Australia.

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:38.000
But at that point, he's, he's Jimmy and it's, um, maybe Nancy Stern, other people, other people, because we took turns being reception at the reception area.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:45.000
If you went off, if you looked to the left, you would see, um, Julian Bond, and he was communications director.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:49.000
When I get there, Mary King is his assistant.

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:55.000
Um, then, yeah, I'm, we didn't have titles, but she was, Julian was the communications director.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:17:02.000
So when I get there, Doddy, Zellner had already left who had been the previous, um, person assisting Julian and communications.

01:17:02.000 --> 01:17:11.000
But so it's Julian and it's Mary King. It's, um, Bobby Yancy, who becomes the second and command at the Schomburg later on.

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:23.000
Um, it stays there for 25 years, but is, you know, is at that point, she's head of, um, I think relationships with the age, now is known as the HBCU is the black campuses.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:27.000
There was Billy Stafford campus travelers. That's right.

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:31.000
Um, and so she's head of that, the campus travelers. Thank you.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:45.000
And then there is Billy Stafford, who was doing some other work with black campuses. And Billy later goes to, um, his wonderful social, urban planner at, um, city college in New York.

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:51.000
But, um, at that point is doing work something around, um, black colleges, but I can't remember exactly what.

01:17:51.000 --> 01:18:01.000
And then, um, there is Jack Menis, who was the main person, he was the head of, of our research department.

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:10.000
And we had this incredible, I mean, he was incredible. You know, he is, he is this crusty, old white guy who, excuse me, drank too much, smoked too much.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:13.000
You know, you would go in his office. It was like a fog. It was like China, you know.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:21.000
Um, and yet he could pull research from a stone. So can, can I mention the thing? Okay.

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:39.000
There was something he did, which became a, um, this is the Mississippi chronology. And it's a chronology of, um, it's called the Mississippi chronology of violence and intimidation in Mississippi since 1961.

01:18:39.000 --> 01:18:56.000
What Jack did was he compiled all of these pages with photos and what was called Watts line. So that was the wide area telephone service. That was like the 800 number that people call into at any hour, either at to our national office or to one of us in the national office.

01:18:56.000 --> 01:19:11.000
If a church were being bombed or, um, somebody had been arrested, um, some violence to vote registration workers, they would call in. And the Watts line meant that it was somebody, and this is when you still had operators.

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:27.000
So somebody say it's, um, uh, Emma, uh, Emma Bell. And Emma Bell calls and says, Hollis Watkins has just been arrested, but she can't say that she calls and calls person to person for Hollis Watkins.

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:36.000
Okay. And so Hollis Watkins, we know. Oh, so that's how it's walk in season. The second CD, second congressional district. We know the number. We know it's about hot.

01:19:36.000 --> 01:19:48.000
Oh, no, no, I'm sorry. Mm-hmm. She would say I'm calling for Emma Bell. Okay. She would call for herself. And then she'd say, this I'm calling a person to person to Emma Bell.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:20:02.000
We would say, this bell is not here right now. Is there a number where we can reach her? And then we would know to call her back. What happened is that at a certain point, the old white operators, telephone operators in Mississippi realize what we were doing.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:22.000
They would then cut off when she's, when the person's tried to give the number. But until that, we at least always had the name. Okay. So then we would hang up and then on this 800 line, the watch line, we would call back for free. She, um, and, and find out that Hollis Watkins was in jail or somebody had been, you know, church had been burned or whatever.

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:32.000
Um, those watch line reports are, are the reports that are compiled for that Mississippi chronology. And I'll go ahead. Okay.

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:46.000
The reason that was so important, having a chronology was that it showed the pattern of racial, of white supremacy. So nobody could say, well, it was just Governor Thompson. He's particularly racist.

01:20:46.000 --> 01:20:59.000
Or it was this, this sheriff in Greenwood or the second, you know, it's the system of racism. And you show that through the pattern of all of these churches, all these people being beaten for voter registration.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:10.000
The, the systemic nature of the white supremacy. And then what they've done to basically, supposedly federally protected rights, just one rough shot over them, right.

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:22.000
I will say I use that. I used it not only to give a chronology when we're doing the films, but more particularly when I leave, um, Boston the first time and it's L.A.

01:21:22.000 --> 01:21:31.000
And there's yet another case of police brutality in L.A. And I'm working for a film company rainbow TV works. This was 80 to 81 82.

01:21:31.000 --> 01:21:44.000
I know from Jack Minnes' chronology. So I say to the people who are working on this, we need a chronology so that we can say so that we can show the pattern of it. And to them, it's like, oh, what a good idea.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:55.000
You know, I would not have known it had it not been for minutes. Okay. When I'm working as the director of information of the United Church of Christ, commission for racial justice, you know, and there's a spade of police brutality.

01:21:55.000 --> 01:22:13.000
You know, it's how the power beach racially motivated violence. It's, you know, Elana Bumper is 69 years old, gets off by officers Sullivan with a shotgun on an eviction notice. It's Michael Stewart, you know, 20 for your age old gets beaten to death in a, in a, for doing graffiti in a New York City subway. It's all of that.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:32.000
But what I say to the committee that we're working with is we need a chronology. Minnes, right. We need a chronology to show it's not just the cop hasn't had enough, you know, sensitivity training. It's because he's in the midst of a systemic racist police department, right. It's like what they're doing. Anyway, so.

01:22:32.000 --> 01:22:44.000
What's the guardian is doing now? You got it. That's right. Because the NRI won't let us keep any stats of this country, right. So the UK is keeping the best stats. Hello.

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:55.000
Which is why I'm glad by the way that in Chicago, I'm going far, I feel bad. I was going to say this. Why in Chicago, they have gone back to that brutal man who tortured blacks.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:23:09.000
And then you know, got finally put up for charges. And I think may have spent some time. I'm not sure. But he is legend. And people kept talking about him because he was brutal. He tortured people.

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:31.000
And got you know, how it got got guilty, please from them when they weren't guilty. We did an eyes on the prize, the Hampton and Clark, Fred Hampton, Mark Clark assassinations in the second series of eyes on the prize, which people are now harkening back to because that's another case where you know the cops said, oh, we had to protect ourselves.

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:47.000
And they found out that all of the bullets were going inside the black panther Chicago office, all of them because the cops were stupid enough to leave the office open. So people in the communities walking through the media is walking through right anyway, the main thing.

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:54.000
And this is the from eyes on the prize second series, the episode of Nation of Law. That's correct.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:24:22.000
And so this is important because one of the things you get is the pattern of it. You know, people always wonder, well, why are they going off? You know, it's like in Detroit. Why would they go? Why would the black community go, you know, totally berserk because some cops are closing a what's called a blind pig there.

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:34.000
And after hours joining, that makes absolutely no sense. Well, if you go back and you find out there was the big four to white and to black cops, which would stop all of these people, even if they were just singing do up, you know, this Detroit, right.

01:24:34.000 --> 01:24:48.000
Do up. We had to explain all of that and eyes on the prize because otherwise it makes no sense. It's the pattern, the systemic pattern of police brutality that always exists in any of these cities. And it's always, always the jumping off point.

01:24:48.000 --> 01:25:02.000
Always, it's something on Steve Faire, who was the white writer and just a great guy. I mean, I, we clashed sometimes, but he was really serious about his stuff and a great writer.

01:25:02.000 --> 01:25:16.000
So I remember at one point we're doing Malcolm X make a plane, right, for American experienced PBS. And I say, you know, the point is that, you know, when you're doing Malcolm, what happens in LA, what happens in New York with the Muslim guy from, you know,

