the food of Islam guy from number seven mosque, you know, that's part of a pattern. And he said, and he actually said, because he was interested, you know, he said, what do you do? I said, the police are an occupying force in these communities.

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:41.000
And I said, no, I know you can't say that. And now he said, why not? And it's a line in narration, right. And you say, that's black side.

01:25:41.000 --> 01:25:53.000
And yeah, black sign. And also I wasn't sure with Orlando, whether Orlando, you know, would be okay with that because it's enough that we're doing just to say enough that we're doing Malcolm X make a plane.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:58.000
Sorry, I meant when you said we were doing the film, I meant it was black side that was doing it.

01:25:58.000 --> 01:26:08.000
Right. No, I thought you were going to say something else in the middle. No. And yes, it is black side. But it's, it's, it's, Henry was not that much involved in Malcolm X make a plane.

01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:29.000
So it really is Orlando was a producer director. I'm the co-producer and Steve is the series writer along with Orlando. So it really is, you know, what, what Orlando and Steve feel, you know, we can get through, you know, American experience at that point.

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:38.000
So I was very happy, you know, that people could see it's an occupying force. And actually I think I said, occupying army. It's like an occupying army.

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:50.000
But that has to do with back to this chronology and the fact that it's systemic and that you have to show that. And so in fact, when we're doing the police brutality, I did a chronology, right. And I'm saying to the groups that are there.

01:26:50.000 --> 01:27:06.000
We need to do a chronology. So people see us not just Ellen or bumpers is not just Michael Stewart is not just. And so they give me early stuff because this is now the mid, this is the mid 80s. So they go back to the 70s, the 60s.

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:15.000
I draw up a chronology. I remember sending a packet out to a journalist, a reporter, black journalist who was with New York News Day.

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:22.000
Because they were based in Long Island, but they then had a New York edition. And they were really good. It was a great, it was a great paper.

01:27:22.000 --> 01:27:34.000
And the reporter calling me and saying, you know, I'm getting this packet and it was not only the press release, but this chronology. And he said, are you a reporter?

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:55.000
And I said, no, I said, and what I said was, I was trained by the movement. I didn't say SNCC, because I figured he wouldn't know what SNCC was. But I said, I was trained by the movement. And so I said, in one of the reasons I did the chronology was because, I didn't say, because Jack Menace told me how to do this, you know. But it's always good. And I was meeting with some young people.

01:27:55.000 --> 01:28:15.000
Oh, BSO, organization of black, oh my goodness, no, OBS, not organizational black survival, organization of black something, it's OBS. And it's a group that's been going on for the last 20 some years. And they were involved also in the Ferguson responses.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:28.000
But they do grassroots community organizing struggle organization for black struggle. So I had been showing our Orangeburg massacre film at Washington University. This is right after Ferguson. So it was this year.

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:44.000
And I'm showing the film and one of the professors, a young black professor, who was there and postdoc and he came up, he introred me. And then he said, would you be interested in speaking with some of the young people who are part of this organization of, what did I just say?

01:28:44.000 --> 01:29:02.000
It'll be a box struggle. And I said, oh, yeah. So the day that I'm the next day, he brings some of them by Wash You and we sit in the cafeteria and we're talking and it's clear. I said, look, I know that the stuff what we did in SNCC is not really, you know, some of it will be useful. But it's a different time.

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:20.000
And I know that it's not just the technical stuff. It's you're dealing with the community that has seen all the stuff that was supposed to change stuff and it hasn't. And the other thing they told me was, they said, well, the other thing is, and actually the young professor said, wasn't professor.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:49.000
Anyway, the young faculty person said, and the other thing was that the movement kind of bypassed St. Louis. So the kind of folks you talk about with, you know, Amsy Moore and Fanny William, he said, that didn't really happen here. And one of the people from OBS says to me, look, every king day, they have the usual Dr. King ceremony. And the black glitterati, come past, you know, and he said, she said, as a matter of fact, she said, and they get out of their limos.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:30:06.000
And she said, I call them the furcoated ones. And she said, they come out with their furcoes. They go into whatever big black church. And then they come back and they go back to the suburbs or wherever. And she said, and so we don't have that grounding that maybe you guys did at that time.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:34.000
Now, I'm sure that their grassroots leaders they have there, but, and they've been working with them, but, you know, it made me realize not everybody had the kind of stuff that we had, nor the kind of cohesive communities that we had cause for whatever I may be not churched. But I know the role of the black church played in the Southern communities where we organized. And, you know, and you could go up on somebody's porch and sit for a while and have some sweet tea and talk before so they could get to know you.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:31:00.000
You can't do that. A cabrini green when it was still existed. You know, in Chicago, so all of that stuff I know is different, but I show them Jack. I show them the chronology right. And I said toward the end, this gets the St. Louis young people in St. Louis and one of one older because she was like 40s. So she said, I'm the older person here. I show them this. They were so it was like, we could use that.

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:28.000
Because I said, you know, one step people see it's not just this and it's not just that and it's not just for any grain. It's like history of it, you know. And it's like when they're finally now saying that like 99% I'm making this up, but certainly over 95% of the cops that have been put up on charges never go to trial. You know, because, you know, they just, it never goes anywhere. So to know that kind of stat from the sixth century, I mean, I mean, I'm sure that's the kind of thing that I'm going to do.

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:57.000
So I'm going to do that kind of stat from the 60s and the 70s, how, how many cops get put up, how many cops, how many judgments are found. And when somebody said $15 million has been put out to victims, all that stuff, those stats are important. Yeah, you can have the protest. And that's important too, but those stats are you can't, you can't deny that kind of stuff. That's Jack. I learned that in, in SNCC, you know. So he's doing the research department.

01:31:57.000 --> 01:32:26.000
Back to the national. We get, we have a, we have a printing press. And so, oh, my goodness. I can't remember the guy Wilson Brown. He was one of them. And then there was another one who married. And they, they went to Antioch. Oh, my goodness, who also ran it. But I'll do Wilson until I can remember any. We had our whole printing press in the basement. Right. So that we didn't have to depend on anybody.

01:32:26.000 --> 01:32:37.000
Saying they wouldn't deprint, wouldn't print a certain leaflet had our own printing press. And then we had, so through communications, we're also sending out the student voice.

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:55.000
Because we knew that the mainstream media wasn't going to print it stuff that we wanted. So we would send that out to the SNCC offices. And so I forgot. We also had a, a friends of SNCC, which was like Philadelphia, Mimi, Mimi,

01:32:55.000 --> 01:33:15.000
Mimi Shaw's mother, Mrs. Shaw's head of friends of, is part of friends of SNCC in Chicago. Or they're all over the country. And so if somebody got arrested, for example, then we get that watch line report, then we would call the Justice Department in the National Office. And then we would call a friends of SNCC person.

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:41.000
So, for example, you would call Mrs. Shaw in Chicago. And she would then call the Sheriff's Office if we had it, well, his home at night, if we had his number, or the office. And then that person would say, Mrs. Shaw would say, look, we know you got, you know, Curtis or Hollis or Mrs. Fanny, Mrs. Hamer. And they'd better come out of the jail the way they went in.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:57.000
So you had, for the first time, the white supremacists in Mississippi know somebody outside, Mrs. Cippy is actually looking at this, you know, even before the summer of 64. We're connecting people to this.

01:33:57.000 --> 01:34:13.000
So we have somebody coordinating, Frances SNCC, and that was Dinky Constante, or Romali. And then there was, she was also doing campus friends of SNCC until Betty Garmin comes in, and she does the campus friends of SNCC.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:26.000
And that was all the campus chapters. UC Berkeley and NYU, University of Chicago, all these campus things. So we can call them. So they're being used as points where we're getting information about the struggles that we're doing.

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:36.000
We're getting photos out. We're getting the student voice out. Press releases is going out. They're trying to get published in their school newspapers information about it.

01:34:36.000 --> 01:34:50.000
If they have any contacts with the local media, they're trying to get that in. So it's this network. I mean out of the national office are these networks of people all over the country whom we're using for fundraising for communications.

01:34:50.000 --> 01:34:56.000
And for fund, yeah, fundraising communications and whatever else.

01:34:56.000 --> 01:35:01.000
What's your contact like with people in the field in Mississippi and Georgia or Pennsylvania?

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:19.000
Yeah, they were, they're calling in. So when, for example, a rebel calls in, she calls into us. But also we had, Margaret Block, for example, she said to me, you remember, I had to call into you. She said, every, every day.

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:27.000
And during the summer of 64, they're calling in to the Jackson office. But before that, they're calling into the national office.

01:35:27.000 --> 01:35:35.000
And I think we might have done it once a day until 64, when it's twice a day, and going into the Jackson office.

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:42.000
But once a day into the national office to say, this is what happened to make sure we know they're still there.

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:56.000
And the main thing is, you know, there's before cell phones. So if somebody didn't have a dime for the coin box on the phone, you wanted to make sure they could get to you.

01:35:56.000 --> 01:36:03.000
So it's called, they're calling in, they're telling us, you know, maybe something incident that's happened.

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:17.000
But the other thing was, Ruby Dars was serious about, you will get me your monthly field reports. And unless you send those to me, you will not get your little $10 a week, which was of course $9.64 after taxes.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:32.000
So she was, I mean, Ruby, and the thing is, people really respected Ruby because I remember Ivan was saying, he said, yeah, people respect a former for what he brought, which was that administrative sense, knowing about history, collect everything.

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:43.000
Knowing how to construct an office, and also just that long range thinking. But Ruby, he said, we knew she really, really cared about us.

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:55.000
And Ivan, who once said to me, he said, you know, when I was in jail, and that was probably an apartment, he said, and I guess was Ivan, an apartment, I'm trying to remember, or was it a local jail?

01:36:55.000 --> 01:37:05.000
When he went in with the trucker stuff, he was in Cleveland, because it was Amazee, that's right. No.

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:13.000
