So it wouldn't automatically collate and staple later we get that. But right then it's pumping off the memograph machine and the stencil. And we're taking and Wilson Brown has taken it up.

01:48:51.000 --> 01:49:03.000
And, you know, so we have it's a, it's a group of people and they're in the work room and you have all this stuff on the, on the table on the work table.

01:49:03.000 --> 01:49:13.000
And somebody would take it off and hand it to the second person. Somebody stapling somebody collating, stapling, putting a folding it, putting it in the stuff, stamping it.

01:49:13.000 --> 01:49:19.000
And so there's a relay. It's a, you know, thing.

01:49:19.000 --> 01:49:31.000
Stemily line. That's the word I'm looking for. So it's an assembly line. So now we also had water bugs. So, and they were the flying water bugs that you get in the South.

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:41.000
So I say that to someone also by the way, if you were on the assembly line, you're always singing freedom songs. Because the work really does go quicker if you sing something.

01:49:41.000 --> 01:49:56.000
And so, you know, everybody's singing and, and we're working and we're doing the stuff. Okay. Now on exec committee meetings, I would, but, but the work room was not large enough usually to hold the staff.

01:49:56.000 --> 01:50:12.000
So we would then, we could get sometimes pass calls, although pass calls really was a black businessman. And so he would charge us. So we would go to Frazier's who really he was so lovely.

01:50:12.000 --> 01:50:22.000
Frazier's basement. We would go down and how our meetings there sometimes. And he would feed you if you didn't have money, my pass call.

01:50:22.000 --> 01:50:51.000
So, you know, you could ask who's in the Atlanta airport now and Frazier's, huh? Well, that could be. That's true. You know, one made money and one. Yeah. But what Frazier's was wonderful. They were just lovely. And, you know, you would go to pass calls for the, they had the bird cage. And so they would have, you know, what's his name in the pips. You know, and they would have all the R&B people come in. And sometimes you would get to meet them and they would be so.

01:50:51.000 --> 01:51:14.000
So, excited to meet the kids and all that kind of stuff, but it was, it was a bird cage. That was a pass calls. But anyway, so I would be taking notes in short hand. Well, the first exact committee meeting I take, it's 33 pages. And it's 33 pages because I'm in awe of all these snake people. Right. They are.

01:51:14.000 --> 01:51:19.000
33 pages. Type. No, 33 pages. Type.

01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:42.000
After you took it in short hand, then you would type it. That's right. That's right. I would take it in short hand. And then I would transcribe my notes. I would type it onto these long green stencils. And which was a problem because, of course, the stencils you couldn't correct except with this little green fluid. So, you had to take the film up the screen up and then put the little green on and then wait for it to dry.

01:51:42.000 --> 01:52:02.000
Put the film down and then hope that you hadn't put too much of this green stuff on because if you did, then when you put typed over it, it would smudge it. And you'd get these smudgy letters all over the place. So, so I was fairly accurate. That was the other thing. I could actually type 90 words a minute with pretty good accuracy.

01:52:02.000 --> 01:52:24.000
Anyway, so I had 33 pages of notes, of minutes, pages of minutes typed out. And then I had to run them out. Now, the problem was I was there late at night. So I would sometimes be there during this period that I'm getting these minutes out. And again, I'm really in awe because these people know more than I have ever heard of.

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:35.000
Not only do I never talk in staff meetings, but I'm also just an awe of all these people who are talking about organizing in ways that I never thought about. They've been through stuff I've never thought about.

01:52:35.000 --> 01:52:53.000
You got, you know, the howard, the nag people who are talking about, you know, Nietzsche. You know, I mean, it's like we're going through that. And also, you know, Biod Rustin and the Sons. But who have organizing techniques and then you've got the Southern young people who know Black History.

01:52:53.000 --> 01:53:05.000
I know Black History in a way that I don't know. So it's all of this. All of this is combining to say, you shut up and take the minutes. Right. So I'm taking the minutes. Okay, get all these things.

01:53:05.000 --> 01:53:15.000
But I have to, but it takes about a week. And I have it in my diary still taking the minutes. I mean, still, still typing the minutes, still typing the minutes.

01:53:15.000 --> 01:53:33.000
Now, the meeting has since disbanded, right. And I think this was the one that we did at IPS, inter-denominational theological seminary, ITS, which was part of the, what becomes the Atlanta University system, inter-denominational theological seminary.

01:53:33.000 --> 01:53:48.000
And so, okay, typing it up, I'm about to run it off and I'm by myself. So I have to go by myself into the workroom. Now, the workroom really does have these flying water bugs. They're big.

01:53:48.000 --> 01:53:54.000
Is that a cockroach? It's like cockroaches, but I thought they were water bugs. Maybe they were cockroaches. They were flying cockroaches.

01:53:54.000 --> 01:54:06.000
Okay, but they flew. That was the main thing. That was operative. Yes, that's true. But that's what the main thing for me was that they flew. What they were, it was that they flew.

01:54:06.000 --> 01:54:21.000
And so they would be, you would come in and they'd be all on the floor. They'd be on the wall. And so you would have to steal yourself for, I'm going to go in here. I'm going to run this off. I'm not going to pay any attention to these things. And I'm just going to run this thing off.

01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:36.000
Yes, if you had to, that's it. And you tried not to crunch anything. You see that's the other thing because it, okay, so doing that and then I finally got it and then I had to mail it, you know, to the various field offices. And that was the other thing.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:53.000
And as a matter of fact, the day that I mailed it off, it's, I have in my diary, the sun is coming up. I have just finished doing the minutes. And I say the birds are singing. You know, it's a wonderful day.

01:54:53.000 --> 01:55:13.000
And so I get that off to whoever was going to disseminate it in the field, you know, and stuff. And so I would do that. And then I would often take the minutes. And other people would too. But because I knew shorthand, you see and typed so quickly, you know, was like, well, Judy can do this because she does this stuff.

01:55:13.000 --> 01:55:30.000
And then I would correct things, you know, because I've always been editing things. And, you know, I wouldn't edit the thoughts. And I don't even think I would actually back then I wouldn't even edit anything else. It would just be whatever I heard. That's true. Yeah.

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:40.000
So I wouldn't try, for example, finish the sentence or do whatever it was whatever they said got into it. Okay. So I would do that.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:43.000
What else?

01:55:44.000 --> 01:55:46.000
I didn't support anything else that was going on. Yeah.

01:55:46.000 --> 01:55:51.000
So talking about the minutes, at a certain point, you and some of the other women have a little protest. Yeah.

01:55:51.000 --> 01:55:53.000
The way I understand it.

01:55:53.000 --> 01:55:57.000
You know, I'll tell you. That's right. So what happens is, um,

01:55:58.000 --> 01:56:07.000
form it. See, I had been saying to form it. Form it. I want to go to the field. I want to go to the field. Okay. Which meant I want to go into Mississippi.

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:13.000
And in my mind, it was Mississippi because that's where all the action was. I knew about Alabama. I knew about Southwest Georgia.

01:56:13.000 --> 01:56:22.000
But most of what we, what I was getting information about, you know, was, because it was Bob. And it was that whole Mississippi thing. It was Miss Bob Moses.

01:56:23.000 --> 01:56:41.000
And that's where it was. Okay. So, um, I keep saying, I want to go to the field. And he was saying, no, um, when it happened, I mean, he did not want to lose a good secretary. Right. So, at one point I end up, oh, I know, he goes someplace.

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:57.000
And Dinky got me a ticket for the, um, the first freedom day in Hattiesburg. That's right. So January, Hattiesburg, 64, Hattiesburg. I'm down there. And I come back for me. It was living.

01:56:58.000 --> 01:57:09.000
But then at some point in here, I get tired of taking the minutes. There were other women who got tired of the minutes. But also they kind of I think wanted to be in the field too.

01:57:09.000 --> 01:57:25.000
But also it was like, we get the secretarial stuff. Now, aside from Jimmy, Jimmy, Jimmy Bolton, um, the guys, see, the thing is the, the, the national office was where you put white people.

01:57:25.000 --> 01:57:37.000
Because white people really risked the lives of local communities and local and and and other blacks and the staff people if they were working in Mississippi.

01:57:38.000 --> 01:57:48.000
You know, um, Sherrod wanted an integrated staff in Southwest Georgia, right? Because he wanted to model what this thing could be.

01:57:48.000 --> 01:57:59.000
And philosophically, he absolutely believed that and he believed that it was based on his, his theological understanding of what was supposed to so beloved community meant you didn't your project as well.

01:58:00.000 --> 01:58:17.000
Other folks were not playing them. And because it really did risk lives. So, um, so what it meant though was that for white people who want to be involved, oftentimes particularly white women who could get black guys killed.

01:58:18.000 --> 01:58:30.000
In the field, um, they were then in the office. So Mary Kings in the office, you know, um, uh, Casey's in Jackson, but she's in Jackson. Casey Hayden is in Jackson.

01:58:31.000 --> 01:58:44.000
But mainly you didn't really have any white women in the field except for Southwest Georgia. And, um, so dinky's there. Nancy Stern is there white women in the national office.

01:58:44.000 --> 01:59:03.000
Um, Mary King. Mary King. Oh, I thought I mentioned her. Yes, Mary Kim. Yeah, that's right. Um, and even for Mark Zucker. I mean, he's not there. He's doing some print stuff too later on when Tommy O'Walkiama comes. Oh, and that's the other part that's part of the national office is the field. There's a print photo department.

01:59:03.000 --> 01:59:32.000
And so Danny line is there. And then Tommy O'Walkiama, who was Tom then, but as part of the nationalist thing where people are really going back to their heritage, right. Tom, Tommy O, then Tom is Japanese Canadian, right. And so he goes to Tommy O. And so that's what he's known out, not known now as as a really premier photographer and has exhibits and wonderful photo book and stuff. Okay. He's, he gets, he comes in through, um, he's doing a lot of work.

01:59:33.000 --> 02:00:02.000
And he's a book that he says similar to elders, cleaver, cleaver's, um, so long ice. He's called Tommy O is calling his book, so long rice. Yes. So he's doing this book. And he mentions how, um, he, he talked at our snake 50th about how he could, I don't know whether you can use us or not. No, don't worry about it. So anyway, he comes into snake through Birmingham. And he arrives in Birmingham. The day that the four little girls are killed.

02:00:02.000 --> 02:00:19.000
He cooks up because there's a, there's a black person in where he lands who says, son, you really don't need to be around here. You need to go to this hotel and stay there because I don't know what's going to be happening. He gets there. He finds Foreman and Danny Lyon and Julian Bond.

02:00:19.000 --> 02:00:34.000
And Foreman says, and, and they find out that he wants to join the movement. And so they, Foreman says, do you have a car? And Tommy O says, yeah, I got a little bug. He said, fine, you can drive us down to the national office. So from Birmingham to Atlanta.

02:00:35.000 --> 02:00:44.000
Tommy O says that for the first week or so, Foreman has him sleeping the floor. And finally, he gets, I had for no money, by the way, because he's not even on staff at that point.

02:00:44.000 --> 02:00:58.000
Tommy O says he looks at Foreman. At some point says to Foreman, you know, I really would like to do something else. And so Foreman then puts them in. I don't know whether Tommy O already knew some stuff around photography. I don't remember.

02:00:58.000 --> 02:01:08.000
In any event, he's then goes into photos. And so then he becomes part of the photo department. So he's down there as well. And how did I get off into photo department?

02:01:08.000 --> 02:01:27.000
Tell us about the minutes. Oh, yes. So, so all these other people are the guys are doing this other stuff, right? But none of the women except for, you know, Mary King is working with Julian and communications. But generally, we're not going in the field. We're not doing other stuff.

02:01:27.000 --> 02:01:45.000
And let me just say, I know why I shouldn't be in the field. I'm from Tarrytown, New York. I don't know anything about southern mores black or white. I don't know this stuff. I'm not church. You know, it's like, please, but you got it. That's it. I still want to go to the field because that's where the action is. Okay.

02:01:45.000 --> 02:02:04.000
So, um, well, I didn't my own quiet way. So we decide. Foreman has gone away. Gone to, I don't know if it was when he went to the UK. I don't see. He goes to London for an anti-aparitate meeting at some point.

02:02:04.000 --> 02:02:20.000
And that's that whole connection that Foreman brings around the South South African anti-aparitate stuff as well as African liberation stuff and Ghana and Kenya and all that stuff. So I'm aware of all of that when I come into SNCC for the first time.

02:02:20.000 --> 02:02:42.000
But at some point, I know in my minute in my diary, I have that I'm going to meet Foreman coming from an international anti-aparitate meeting in London. And I'm going to meet him at the Atlanta airport and how excited I am to hear about, you know, I'm excited to think about what I'm going to hear from him.

02:02:42.000 --> 02:03:00.000
But I don't know if that's that time because he used to go away. You know, he'd do fundraising meetings. He'd be at the Friends of SNCC stuff. In any event, he had gone away to some meeting and or fundraising party. And I, and we decide and I don't know how we get to this.

02:03:00.000 --> 02:03:14.000
Ruby Dars, Dinky, Mary King, and who and I, and seeing me there was a fifth person, was somebody else in the picture? Oh, Bobbi Ansi.

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:15.000
And Mildred.

02:03:15.000 --> 02:03:17.000
And Mildred and Bobbi Ansi.

02:03:17.000 --> 02:03:20.000
Dinky's not your right. No, she wasn't in that.

02:03:20.000 --> 02:03:27.000
And she wouldn't have been with Mildred as a matter of fact now that I think about it. Okay. So Mildred was Foreman's first wife.

02:03:27.000 --> 02:03:44.000
Okay. So you're right. It is Mildred, Mary King, Bobbi Ansi, and Ruby Dars and I. And we made up little signs, little placards that said no freedom, no, no minutes till something comes, freedom's something. What was it?

02:03:44.000 --> 02:03:48.000
Freedom comes to justice comes to Atlanta office.

02:03:48.000 --> 02:03:56.000
That's it. That's right. And freedom now, you know what I mean? So we're standing up there and he comes back from whatever, you know, he comes back from the New York Times.

02:03:56.000 --> 02:04:06.000
And he comes back into the office and he sees us in my little area with and we're sitting on the floor with our little protest signs.

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:14.000
And he is behind us because clearly I think it was Danny. I'm sure it was Danny who takes his photo.

02:04:14.000 --> 02:04:25.000
So it's a staged photo, but it's after Foreman comes back and sees us sitting and saying, because I think Foreman's in the back of the picture with a sign.

02:04:25.000 --> 02:04:33.000
Oh, I don't remember him having a sign, but he is. That's why I was saying he's in the back, but I don't remember him having a sign, but I'm not sure about that.

02:04:33.000 --> 02:04:39.000
Yeah, I don't know that we would have let him have a sign, but I don't know about that. And I would need, I actually have a copy of that.

02:04:39.000 --> 02:05:05.000
So we do that. Now what's interesting about that is that when Foreman does the second edition of making of a black revolutionary in his second edition, he says that his editor, and I can't remember, she was a SNCC staff person. I can't remember who.

02:05:05.000 --> 02:05:21.000
No, not white female person. I can't remember who it is. I may or may not remember it. Anyway, says to him that he should do more on the Women's Liberation Movement.

02:05:21.000 --> 02:05:37.000
And so he does a section. And in it, he says that, a woman says, you should talk about this and I talk about the sit in your office. And he says in this intro.

02:05:37.000 --> 02:05:57.000
So I talked to the women in the office. And I, and no, no, he said the women in the office came to me and asked me what I about how they could best do this, you know, get, come to the attention of the men in the organization.

02:05:57.000 --> 02:06:19.000
And I suggested that them they do a sit in in my office, says, for him. And usually what I'm saying is I actually have the book because I read from it. And what he says is, so I suggested they do a sit in and that they do placards and that they do this, you know, sit in and it will come to the, you know, the attention of the guys.

02:06:19.000 --> 02:06:35.000
Okay, now he comes out with this next edition while I'm in Boston working on the second, let's see, that came out in the 80s, I guess, mid 80s. So I'm working on think on the first series of eyes on the prize, I think.

02:06:35.000 --> 02:06:47.000
And I'm reading this on the train. And I see this section and I still have in my copy what an exclamation point, exclamation point in blue highlighter.

02:06:47.000 --> 02:06:59.000
So I get down there to the book party and I wait till the end and it's just, it's just he and I at the end. And he saw me in my book and I said, for him.

02:06:59.000 --> 02:07:09.000
What are you talking about that you suggested this sitting, you know the where the ones who did this, he said, well, that's not what I remember.

02:07:09.000 --> 02:07:21.000
It's like, so what do you say behind that? You know, now fast forward, we're at the snick 40s and Jackson. And was that, I think it was a Jackson, wasn't it?

02:07:21.000 --> 02:07:31.000
It's a 40s, it's a Duke. Duke was a Duke, we were at Duke, you're right. And I'll line a panel with Ivan Ho and Foreman and somebody else.

