So it was interesting because at the same time that this is happening, I also felt the most powerful I've ever felt.

02:08:05.000 --> 02:08:14.000
I always felt that I had no limits. You know, the people let me do, and it really was let me because I had no real power.

02:08:14.000 --> 02:08:24.000
You know, it's like, they let me, they let me do stuff that it went like the residential freedom school. I come up with this idea after 64.

02:08:24.000 --> 02:08:31.000
Let's do a residential freedom school. Now, it means that it must have been actually, it must have been sometime in 65.

02:08:31.000 --> 02:08:43.000
Because I'd already been to Cordial Southwest Georgia. And I've been the staff person there. And so anyway, I come back with this idea.

02:08:43.000 --> 02:08:51.000
We'll get, and my thing was, okay, we'll get the energy of the southern kids and the sense that you really can change things.

02:08:51.000 --> 02:09:03.000
And together with some of the young people who are associated with the Friends of Snick Offices. And so we ended up going through in Rocharp, who was head of the Chicago Snick Office then.

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:11.000
And so we based it out of Chicago for the northern end. And then we were going to go back to Cordial for the southern end.

02:09:11.000 --> 02:09:21.000
We were going to do three weeks in one place and three weeks in the other. And the idea was that we would have a whole curriculum.

02:09:21.000 --> 02:09:30.000
And, okay, I had this whole idea about what would happen. And the northern kids, the advantage of putting these together is that you get the energy of the southern kids.

02:09:30.000 --> 02:09:37.000
And the northern kids' reality of this is just up south. And there would be this kind of inter...

02:09:37.000 --> 02:09:54.000
You'd have this... there's a word for that. Interaction, yes. So I come up with this idea. And I remember Ivan was saying to me, yes, interesting. He said, why don't you put it down? Let me see a draft of the proposal. Maybe I can see if I can get it funded.

02:09:54.000 --> 02:10:03.000
And he says the same thing. Also, the stokey says, stokey says, yeah, let me know when you want me to come and I'll come up. Charlie says the same thing.

02:10:03.000 --> 02:10:10.000
Nobody says to me, you have never done this before in your life. What the hell do you think you're thinking of?

02:10:10.000 --> 02:10:20.000
If I had been those other people, I would have said, no, no, no, no, no, we're not giving this to you. Nobody says this. Nobody ever said this to men or women.

02:10:20.000 --> 02:10:31.000
There was a sense that if it seemed like a halfway decent idea was part of the agenda of the organization.

02:10:31.000 --> 02:10:40.000
That you know, go for it. And so I haven't ho, somehow got this funding because I know I didn't. I knew how to write a proposal.

02:10:40.000 --> 02:10:48.000
Or I knew I must have seen proposals written because I certainly didn't know coming off Swarth and West Campus.

02:10:48.000 --> 02:10:56.000
So I learned all this stuff in how you do this in SNCC. And I do this, but again, it was go for it.

02:10:56.000 --> 02:11:00.000
And this is, I don't know, when you have Charlie Cove.

02:11:00.000 --> 02:11:05.000
That's right, it's the Stokeley Carmichael. That's right.

02:11:05.000 --> 02:11:16.000
So, yeah, it was the sense of being limitless within the agenda of the organization, the philosophy of the organization.

02:11:16.000 --> 02:11:21.000
And if you got people to support you, I mean, you couldn't just decide to do this.

02:11:21.000 --> 02:11:26.000
Clearly, there was some support that had come through somewhere, probably, on Chaudh by Ivano.

02:11:26.000 --> 02:11:29.000
That had allowed me to go ahead and move with this.

02:11:29.000 --> 02:11:34.000
